												L'Ombre Dans L'Eau Eau de Toilette by
												Diptyque is a Floral fragrance for women.
												L'Ombre Dans L'Eau Eau de Toilette was launched
												in 1983. The nose behind this fragrance is Serge
												Kalouguine.
											

											

												

													L'Ombre Dans L'Eau ("Shadow in the water") is a female
													fragrance from 1983, based on the unusual and
													beautiful harmony of black currant leaf and Bulgarian
													rose, which blend perfectly together. This perfume was
													created by Serge Kalouguine, a famous French perfumer
													who dedicated 30 years of his life to the house of
													Fragonard. Read more about this fragrance in the
													article L'Ombre dans L'Eau ("Shadow in the water")
													from Diptyque.

																				I own versions of the EDT from 2023,
																				2019 (limited edition) and circa
																				2000.


																				The current version is the greenest in
																				the opening, which I personally prefer,
																				and has a nice sillage for the first
																				half-hour, fading rather quickly to a
																				skin scent which is mostly about cassis.
																				Rose is a supporting note, to my nose. I
																				get about 4 hours of longevity, and that
																				is if I overspray. 


																				The 2019 edition is sweeter for me with
																				slightly better longevity.


																				Lastly, the ~2000 formulation is a
																				different beast altogether. It really
																				is, on my skin, a blackcurrant fragrance
																				with very little stem. Granted, the top
																				notes may have evaporated somewhat, but
																				the bottle was entirely full when I got
																				it, so I doubt this is very
																				substantially the case. The rose is also
																				much more cogent and richer than in
																				either of the later versions I own. It
																				also reads as rather less fresh, but I
																				don’t get the impression that this is
																				much in virtue of aging. I also get
																				significantly better sillage and
																				longevity, though not as much as with
																				the current EDP, which I also own.
																				


																				Suffice it to say that if you find the
																				green top notes of the current EDT too
																				bracing or astringent, I would recommend
																				trying to seek out a vintage (which
																				comes in a square bottle). If you
																				otherwise love the fragrance, I think
																				you’ll really enjoy it.

																				central white rose is the star of the
																				show to my nose, but it’s beautifully
																				complemented by the shadowy cassis and
																				slightly marine ambergris. it conjures
																				up an image of a secluded faerie garden
																				under a cloudy sky, or even
																				shakespeare’s tragic heroine ophelia.


																				contrary to diptyque’s current
																				marketing, i hesitate to call l’ombre
																				dans l’eau unisex; it’s almost
																				hyperfeminine, so confrontational in its
																				bracing green stemminess that i can see
																				how its cold, elegant confidence can be
																				perceived as having a masculine edge.
																				the notes aren’t traditionally
																				“seductive” in that they eschew warmth
																				and skank of any kind, yet i constantly
																				get compliments wearing this from people
																				of all genders (especially other women
																				who want to know what i’m wearing!)


																				i’ve also seen it described as gothic by
																				others before, though i can only imagine
																				it being gothic the same way early
																				cocteau twins’ music was— melancholy,
																				yes, but comparatively romantic and
																				delicate, in stark contrast to ‘80s
																				heavy-hitters like dior poison. speaking
																				of cocteau twins, this scent really
																				reminds me of their music as a whole,
																				and i’m looking forward to layering it
																				with ethereal wave, the new release from
																				liis fragrances that’s directly inspired
																				by them.


																				the reviews on this perfume seem to be
																				rather polarized, and i can’t say i
																				blame anyone for that. the scent profile
																				isn’t the most conventional, and both
																				sillage and longevity admittedly aren’t
																				the best. but for anyone looking for a
																				unique rose or a true, green freshie,
																				l’ombre dans l’eau is THAT girl. that
																				true, one of a kind, wistfully aloof
																				it-girl.

																				character scent for me. She stands out
																				like a sore thumb in my collection of
																				warm, spicy and heady perfumes. I
																				remember smelling this in store some
																				years back and I could not stop thinking
																				about the tangy tartness. A month or so
																				passed and I had to treat myself to a
																				full bottle, it was a visceral reaction,
																				I caved in to the craving. 


																				The sharp slightly sour blackcurrant
																				note is undoubtedly the star of the
																				show. And it does indeed smell a lot
																				like Diptyque's well renowned Baies
																				candle. with which I was already
																				familiar and fond of. In this case I
																				much prefer the edt to it's more floral
																				edp counterpart, which is a first for
																				me. Decidedly green and fruity yet
																				bitter, it is not a sexy or alluring
																				perfume. It definitely reminds me of the
																				90s in it's androgynous crispness. But
																				equally it has this whimsical 'Wind in
																				the Willows/Enid Blyton' mystique about
																				it, an air of 'English Country Garden'
																				from days of yore. I'm a London girl
																				born in the late 80s, but if you are
																				familiar with the 1930s illustrations of
																				the Flower Fairies by Cicely Mary Barker
																				it reminds me of how I imagine they
																				would smell! It is reminiscent of
																				rambling through the countryside,
																				alongside a path of fresh cut grass and
																				juicy berry bushes after rain.


																				Definitely unisex, even leaning slightly
																				masculine. It smells like a luscious
																				garden, you could lean into the theme
																				and wear it in the rain with your
																				wellies, on a rural walk. Or use it
																				counterintuitively - as an injection of
																				freshness on a hot, sticky day or to
																				spritz as a cobweb buster when you
																				shouldn't have had that extra glass of
																				wine the night before. As someone who is
																				generally averse to citrus perfumes,
																				l'Ombre dans l'Eau bridges the gap where
																				a freshie should be in my fragrance
																				wardrobe, and gives me this sense of
																				romantic nostalgia for halcyon days from
																				before I was even born, if that isn't
																				the magic transportative power of
																				fragrance, then I don't know what is!

																				〰✴L’ombre Dans l’Eau (EDT): nostalgic
																				and romantic ✴〰


																				Based on the notes I would have never
																				purchased this product (I usually prefer
																				sweeter and less fresh/ floral scents),
																				but I had to change my mind: I am
																				completely in love with this
																				fragrance.

																				The label design perfectly evokes the
																				mood of the scent: green and slightly
																				aquatic, romantic and very nostalgic.
																				It's an inoffensive scent, it really
																				calms me down, so much so that I put it
																				on before I go to sleep. It's a clean,
																				natural, non-soapy scent. Youthful, yet
																				sophisticated and suitable for people of
																				all ages. It's dreamy, but in a sort of
																				"dark" way… I think that’s explained by
																				the olfactory accident of this
																				fragrance: blackcurrant leaves. Speaking
																				about that, when I noticed that there
																				was mention of fruity accords I was
																				skeptical, because I imagined some kind
																				of sticky sweet fruit, but that's not
																				the case at all, we're more on the green
																				side. It's the rose that brings a floral
																				and sweet (not cloying) note, and
																				because of that many people think it's a
																				"women's" fragrance… I completely
																				disagree, it’s totally a gender-neutral
																				fragrance (although for me all
																				fragrances have no gender a priori, as
																				well as clothes...but that's a whole
																				different story).


																				This was my first Diptyque (as well as
																				my first niche) perfume. I sprayed the
																				EDP on my arm in the boutique, but I
																				wasn't impressed until the next day,
																				when I woke up and realized the scent
																				was still there. The EDP is incredibly
																				persistent and has a great sillage, the
																				EDT is more subtle and intimate, but
																				still great. EDT and EDP have pretty
																				much the same notes in my opinion, only
																				the intensity changes due to the
																				concentration of the perfume. I think
																				the EDT is a safe blind buy, and is
																				wearable for any occasion. Probably more
																				a spring/summer scent, but I like it all
																				year long, day and night.


																				Another thing I have to mention about
																				L'Ombre Dans l'Eau is that the body
																				products are amazing as well. I own the
																				body cream and the solid parfum, they
																				both smell amazing. Usually perfumes are
																				very volatile and last very little on my
																				skin, but in the case of L'Ombre Dans
																				l'Eau products they have good longevity
																				(obviously not as much as EDT and EDP,
																				but it's remarkable). I highly recommend
																				body cream and solid perfume, great for
																				layering too!


																				The last thing I have to mention about
																				this fragrance is its power of making me
																				feel good in my own skin! It makes me
																				feel confident. I don’t care what people
																				think, and let me tell you that’s new to
																				me: I’ve always been looking for scents
																				that are persistent and have a strong
																				sillage until now because I wanted to
																				make a good impression. Now I just don’t
																				care anymore: it’s intimate scent that
																				make me feel confident.


																				Setting & feelings: You’re in a
																				beautiful garden sitting by a lake,
																				under a willow tree and surrounded by
																				roses. You’re drinking a black currant
																				tea and looking around: this place is so
																				beautiful and you enjoy being there, but
																				something feels strange. It’s nostalgia,
																				hitting. Maybe you’re missing someone
																				special…?


																				Overall: 8/10

																			ambergeese09/15/21 10:44
																		

																	

																	

																		

																			

																				Straight out of the bottle and in the
																				first seconds on skin, this is pure
																				fresh green garden nostalgia. This is
																				nothing to do with that aquatic calone
																				melony cucumber perfume scent, and
																				everything to do with the smell of the
																				spiney, spiney, hard and bitter dirty
																				skin of a homegrown cucumber, freshly
																				plucked.


																				The real master stroke of this one is,
																				in my opinion, that opening fresh
																				greenness. I spend my whole summers
																				elbows-deep in the currant bushes,
																				smelling the fruits and leaves, and I've
																				never met a currant leaf fragrance that
																				definitely hits that smell on the head,
																				but this one does correctly approximate
																				the aspects of fresh green and bitter
																				snapping wet leaves in equal measure. So
																				many green scents go aquatic and
																				calone-y, or else they go too clean in a
																				sappy, lactonic sort of direction.
																				L'Ombre Dans L'Eau is neither of these,
																				because it's not afraid of the
																				bitterness necessary for a true,
																				realistic fresh green garden scent. The
																				bitter, sour, vinegar-y nuances of that
																				tomato leaf, cucumber skin sort of scent
																				are precisely what makes the green here
																				so realistic. I wish it would stick
																				around longer.


																				Within a minute, the green smells are
																				joined by the freshest, loveliest
																				fragrance rose I've ever worn. It
																				reminds me so incredibly much of my
																				proto-fragrance days when I'd wear just
																				a hint of a single floral essential oil,
																				jasmine or neroli or rose. This is an
																				identical pure rose oil, but it's mire
																				than just the oil. It has photorealistic
																				softness and greenness that makes me
																				think of smelling blooming roses and
																				wishing that exact perfect smell would
																				translate to perfumery. Roses (and, to
																				an extent, florals in general) make me
																				wary in fragrance, because I loathe the
																				way they can end up soapy, plastic,
																				artificial. So many florals I've smelled
																				are just odd hand soap scents that make
																				me forget the scent comes from flowers
																				originally. But this? This rose is as
																				real as the night, creamy and pale
																				pink.


																				Oddly enough, I get no fruit here! I
																				grew up growing currants and am very
																				familiar with what they smell like, but
																				I don't get any scents I'd call fruity.
																				The green and wet and bitter aspects of
																				this do remind me of weaving through the
																				wet currant bushes to pluck fruit in
																				between summer showers, but nothing here
																				is fruity like a pie or a still life
																				bowl of fruit or a cupcake. I'm hesitant
																				about fruit, especially in "clean"
																				scents, as I feel they go straight into
																				shampoo territory, but I'm relieved not
																				to get any of that here.


																				As the rose continues to dominate, some
																				soft hints of warm, ambery sweetness
																				start to peak through. The ambergris and
																				musk provide a touch of sweet and warm
																				that is, at first, a lovely and pleasant
																				contrast to the fresh outdoor smells of
																				the rest of the pyramid. In time,
																				though, I fear these lead into a dull
																				finish and make for an uninspired base
																				of the pyramid.


																				From 3 hours in and onward, something
																				odd happens: the scent becomes almost
																				powdery, in a rooty way, like orris
																				root. It's the fusty, dirty,
																				sickly-sweet root powder smell that
																				enchanted me in Perry Woman, just toned
																				down a bit. This accord creeps in out of
																				nowhere, with nothing but a tiny touch
																				of ambery warmth to warn of its arrival,
																				so I honestly have no idea what it's
																				made of or how it's done. It's a touch
																				of nondescript sweetness, like a
																				cupboard holding an expired bottle of
																				Hypnotic Poison, that isn't unpleasant,
																				but it is dull. It makes me miss the
																				greens and rose and go rooting for them
																				in the powder, where there are still
																				hints of what was there before, but
																				they're faint as a dream that's failed
																				to become a memory. Through the latter
																				two thirds of the 9 hours or so that
																				this lasts, I find myself missing the
																				first few hours dearly, with their
																				perfect greens and rose. Perhaps that
																				nondescript amber sweetness is more
																				welcome in colder months.


																				The minimalism and expert blending and
																				composition are really striking in this
																				one. Wet, wild garden greens to the most
																				realistic rose to an odd rooty powder.
																				It's a simple enough sequence, but the
																				way each phase obscures what comes next
																				and then elegantly gives way is
																				absolutely masterful. The first few
																				minutes and hours of this one in
																				particular are something absolutely
																				delicious I'd like to bathe in.


																				So often, I take in a fresh or green
																				scent and am disappointed in comparing
																				the experience to any mundane whiff of
																				air outdoors, even far away from
																				anything green. Scents billed as clean
																				present either a hotel soap or some
																				uncanny valley smell of earthless,
																				purified sap. Somehow, this one is fresh
																				and lovely without going in either of
																				those directions. Somehow, L'Ombre Dans
																				L'Eau captures something of the fresh
																				pleasure of a deep breath of real
																				outdoor air better than anything else
																				I've smelled so far. It brings me back
																				to all kinds of green garden activities,
																				watering and collecting cucumbers and
																				tomatoes and currants, and the rose is
																				delightful. This is delicious.

																				spend a few moments harvesting the
																				ripest berries you can find. Next, you
																				carefully select and cut a handful of
																				the roses to create a long-stem bouquet.
																				


																				Carrying the bouquet in one hand and a
																				sachet of currant berries in the other,

																				walking barefoot down the trail that

																				water straight to the center of your

																			ionantha07/02/20 11:23
																		

																	

																	

																		

																			

																				Oof. Every so often a fragrance goes a
																				little nuts on you and pulls weird
																				notes, and this was one of those for me.
																				I'm intrigued by unusual perfumes and
																				loved the description of this one, but
																				it's weird and unappealing on my skin's
																				chemistry.


																				When I dabbed L'Ombre on from a sample
																				vial, the first minute or so was a blast
																				of "old cigarette." Tobacco and tomato
																				are both in the Solanaceae (nightshade)
																				plant family, so this was an
																				interesting, if unpleasant, variation on
																				the notes experienced by others. It was
																				very, uh, different.


																				After that opening came the rose, which
																				was quickly dominated by the more heady
																				cassis leaf. At this point, I too
																				smelled the hint of tomato leaf. The
																				rose note seems to come and go as the
																				perfume develops, and it resembles
																				Lutens' Sa Majeste la Rose. I prefer it
																				when it's more rosy; the notes seems
																				more balanced at those times. When the
																				cassis leaf dominates, it's too intense
																				for me. There is also a little bit of a
																				vintage note that I can't quite
																				identify, that reminds me of Houbigant's
																				Quelques Fleurs Royale (and to a lesser
																				extent the regular QF).


																				After an hour or so, L'Ombre faded to a
																				skin scent on my wrist. Imagine drinking
																				a blackcurrant spritzer or Ruby Mist tea
																				in an enclosed rose garden, with the
																				strong scent of ripe berries on hedges
																				all around. The vintage note is still
																				there, with hints of green and musk. On
																				me it feels like a rather mature
																				fragrance in a few ways, and this has
																				strengthened my suspicion that big berry
																				scents just aren't my jam. :)


																				I came close to scrubbing it on this hot
																				summer day, but I may try it again in
																				cooler weather to see what changes. I
																				can imagine that this is a fragrance
																				that has some seasonal variation, as
																				well as skin chemistry variation. I'd
																				really love to have an evocative green
																				"secret garden" sort of scent, but this
																				might not be the one.


																				Update: the drydown is all rose on me,
																				and a more delicate one than before. It
																				almost smells like a different

																			ionantha07/02/20 11:23
																		

																	

																	

																		

																			

																				Oof. Every so often a fragrance goes a
																				little nuts on you and pulls weird
																				notes, and this was one of those for me.
																				I'm intrigued by unusual perfumes and
																				loved the description of this one, but
																				it's weird and unappealing on my skin's
																				chemistry.


																				When I dabbed L'Ombre on from a sample
																				vial, the first minute or so was a blast
																				of "old cigarette." Tobacco and tomato
																				are both in the Solanaceae (nightshade)
																				plant family, so this was an
																				interesting, if unpleasant, variation on
																				the notes experienced by others. It was
																				very, uh, different.


																				After that opening came the rose, which
																				was quickly dominated by the more heady
																				cassis leaf. At this point, I too
																				smelled the hint of tomato leaf. The
																				rose note seems to come and go as the
																				perfume develops, and it resembles
																				Lutens' Sa Majeste la Rose. I prefer it
																				when it's more rosy; the notes seems
																				more balanced at those times. When the
																				cassis leaf dominates, it's too intense
																				for me. There is also a little bit of a
																				vintage note that I can't quite
																				identify, that reminds me of Houbigant's
																				Quelques Fleurs Royale (and to a lesser
																				extent the regular QF).


																				After an hour or so, L'Ombre faded to a
																				skin scent on my wrist. Imagine drinking
																				a blackcurrant spritzer or Ruby Mist tea
																				in an enclosed rose garden, with the
																				strong scent of ripe berries on hedges
																				all around. The vintage note is still
																				there, with hints of green and musk. On
																				me it feels like a rather mature
																				fragrance in a few ways, and this has
																				strengthened my suspicion that big berry
																				scents just aren't my jam. :)


																				I came close to scrubbing it on this hot
																				summer day, but I may try it again in
																				cooler weather to see what changes. I
																				can imagine that this is a fragrance
																				that has some seasonal variation, as
																				well as skin chemistry variation. I'd
																				really love to have an evocative green
																				"secret garden" sort of scent, but this
																				might not be the one.


																				Update: the drydown is all rose on me,
																				and a more delicate one than before. It
																				almost smells like a different
																				perfume.


																				Definitely one to try on your skin
																				before you buy it!
